	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} Surface ozone ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) pollution levels are strongly correlated with daytime surface temperatures, especially in highly polluted regions. This correlation is nonlinear and occurs through a variety of temperature-dependent mechanisms related to {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} precursor emissions, lifetimes, and reaction rates, making the reproduction of temperature sensitivities – and the projection of associated human health risks – a complex problem. Here we explore the summertime {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}–temperature relationship in the United States and Europe using the chemical transport model GEOS-Chem. We remove the temperature dependence of several mechanisms most frequently cited as causes of the {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}–temperature “climate penalty”, including PAN decomposition, soil {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{\textit{x}}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} emissions, biogenic volatile organic compound (VOC) emissions, and dry deposition. We quantify the contribution of each mechanism to the overall correlation between {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} and temperature both individually and collectively. Through this analysis we find that the thermal decomposition of PAN can explain, on average, 20\&thinsp;\% of the overall {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}–temperature correlation in the United States. The effect is weaker in Europe, explaining 9\&thinsp;\% of the overall {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}–temperature relationship. The temperature dependence of biogenic emissions contributes 3\&thinsp;\% and 9\&thinsp;\% of the total {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}–temperature correlation in the United States and Europe on average, while temperature-dependent deposition (6\&thinsp;\% and 1\&thinsp;\%) and soil {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}NO$_{\textrm{\textit{x}}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} emissions (10\&thinsp;\% and 7\&thinsp;\%) also contribute. Even considered collectively these mechanisms explain less than 46\&thinsp;\% of the modeled {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}–temperature correlation in the United States and 36\&thinsp;\% in Europe. We use commonality analysis to demonstrate that covariance with other meteorological phenomena such as stagnancy and humidity can explain the bulk of the remainder of the {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}–temperature correlation. Thus, we demonstrate that the statistical correlation between {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} and temperature alone may greatly overestimate the direct impacts of temperature on {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}, with implications for the interpretation of policy-relevant metrics such as climate penalty.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
